ENTRY       EC 1.17.2.1                 Enzyme
NAME        nicotinate dehydrogenase (cytochrome);
            nicotinic acid hydroxylase;
            nicotinate hydroxylase
CLASS       Oxidoreductases;
            Acting on CH or CH2 groups;
            With a cytochrome as acceptor
SYSNAME     nicotinate:cytochrome 6-oxidoreductase (hydroxylating)
REACTION    nicotinate + a ferricytochrome + H2O = 6-hydroxynicotinate + a ferrocytochrome + 2 H+ [RN:R09473]
ALL_REAC    R09473
SUBSTRATE   nicotinate [CPD:C00253];
            ferricytochrome [CPD:C00923];
            H2O [CPD:C00001]
PRODUCT     6-hydroxynicotinate [CPD:C01020];
            ferrocytochrome [CPD:C00924];
            H+ [CPD:C00080]
COMMENT     This two-component enzyme from Pseudomonas belongs to the family of xanthine dehydrogenases, but differs from most other members of this family. While most members contain an FAD cofactor, the large subunit of this enzyme contains three c-type cytochromes, enabling it to interact with the electron transfer chain, probably by delivering the electrons to a cytochrome oxidase. The small subunit contains a typical molybdopterin cytosine dinucleotide(MCD) cofactor and two [2Fe-2S] clusters [1].
